Chapter One
Korun
It was 4:30 in the morning of the Itanian time. Korun hated waking up so early. Mainly because he had to be responsible for waking up the rest of the squad. He quietly got out of bed, put on his combat gear, fastened his tactical vest, and packed his belongings from the storage cabinet. He carefully picked up a small special box. He shouldered his rifle, hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. The helmet was equipped with a full set of gear, including a respirator, goggles, and other necessary items. After checking his ammunition pouch, he quietly stepped out of the barracks, his boots making crunching sounds on the muddy and icy ground.
He took out a lighter from his jacket pocket and a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a gentle puff and then opened the door. In the past week, he had to think hard just to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used a preset alarm clock, because half the time it didn't ring, and the speaker only emitted a faint hissing sound.
"Time to wake them up?" Korun turned around and saw Captain Nemetsi approaching.
"Yes," Korun answered.
"What are you planning to do this time?"
Korun hadn't had time to answer when the door opened, and Harris, Kres, and several others rushed out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," Kres said.
"What woke you up?" Korun asked.
"First of all, we really don't want to see what method you're going to use to wake everyone up today. Second, the first person to get up from the squad can have priority for breakfast," said a soldier named Laviak. "You know how bad the breakfast is."
Korun said, "You're right, Corporal Laviak." He reached out and pressed the switch. A shrill alarm immediately sounded in the barracks. He heard people shouting inside, along with a flurry of hurried footsteps.
"Goodness, Valturi," Nemetsi said. "I thought they should have learned by now to get up with you."
"My new recruits did that," Korun pointed to Harris, Kres, and Laviak. "But to be honest, their squad leaders and platoon commanders knew to get up before the soldiers."
A few seconds later, the rest of the squad ran out. They were all dressed and ready. Some of the new recruits looked drowsy, while others seemed very annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Korun said cheerfully.
"Forgive me, sir, but why did you wake us up that way?" asked a squad member (corporal).
"Because those regular alarm clocks are just garbage. And Daybreak never sleeps in."
"Bring your personal belongings," Korun continued. As a lieutenant and the deputy commander of the platoon, he had the responsibility to assist the platoon commander, Captain Boldin Xiao, in supervising and leading the platoon. "We won't be returning. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for final checks and to bring today's rations."
The members of Exodus Platoon dispersed quickly. They were part of the Second Assault Regiment of the Second Group Army. Before the merger, they were originally two independent platoons, Cohort and Dagger. This was an elite platoon, and Korun felt complex emotions about being promoted to lieutenant, with many reasons behind it.
Korun and First Squad Leader Nemetsi walked side by side along the brightly lit road of the base, with lights powered by generators on both sides. Most of the lights were red, helping them avoid enemy bombers. To counter them, Daybreak has begun using "wild weasel" tactics both in the air and on the ground.
"A new day, a new mission for the Hell's Vanguard," Nemetsi joked dryly. "Where are they going to send us this time?"
"Some frontline base outside the city of Ianlos. We're being sent to support the ground attack," Korun said, taking a puff of his cigarette. He somewhat blamed Kres for getting him into the habit, but thinking back on the past year, they had experienced countless battles, so he let it go, saying nothing.
"That's terrible. The front lines are really tough right now," Nemetsi whispered. "All the messages we get here are 'support the war, assist the Kurgan front,' but why not support the Houlan front?"
"Well said, brother," Korun said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We'll be going with the First Armor Squad, no need to walk. Captain Xiao should be there."
"Captain Xiao ordered us to ride with him?" Nemetsi asked in surprise.
"Yes. To be honest, he's not as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not unbearable either."
Korun raised his thumb and index finger, pressing against his throat's microphone, and at the same time moved his pack onto his back. "All units of Exodus Platoon, assemble at the west zone vehicle depot after completing the mission. We will depart with the First Armor Squad at 05:00."
Every few seconds, he received replies from the squad leaders. When they first arrived, Harris, Kres, and Laviak were lower-ranking corporals. Since basic training on Earth, the four of them had been close friends. Korun felt like he had known them for a long time, though it had been less than two years. They were all squad leaders, but since a week ago, when the previous platoon leader was shot by a Daybreak sniper and retired due to injuries, Kres began leading the Second Squad.
When they arrived at the vehicle depot, Korun and Nemetsi's eyes landed on approximately eight Kratos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. Crew members were running around, ensuring their war machines were in good condition. Korun quickly found Captain Xiao, Bo Dalin, who was talking with the commander of the armor squad. As they approached, Captain Xiao looked at them and came forward, his usual indifferent face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemetsi... Lieutenant Valturi..." he said. Korun slowed his pace. Captain Xiao looked at Korun's holstered pistol and then raised his head. "Has the squad already been prepared?"
